  "prompt": "I am in Tier 2 general visa for 3 years, I am in It. most of client not choosing the Tier 2 general visa, they are not interested in Contract offer?",
  "response": "If you are on a Tier 2 General Visa (now known as a Skilled Worker visa) in the UK, it's important to understand the constraints it places on your employment options, especially if you're considering contracting work. Here are some points to consider:\n\n1. **Visa Sponsorship:** Tier 2 General visas require a sponsoring employer who has a valid sponsorship license. If you choose to work as a contractor, you need a contract with a company that is willing to sponsor your visa. Many companies prefer not to go through the sponsorship process due to the additional administrative burden and cost.\n\n2. **Type of Employment:** The Skilled Worker visa typically ties you to one employer, meaning you cannot freelance or contract for multiple clients directly. The visa is intended for direct, long-term employment with the sponsoring company.\n\n3. **Permitted Work:** The type of work you can do and who you can work for is dictated by the job description and salary stated in your Certificate of Sponsorship (CoS). Venturing outside these parameters without updating your visa can be problematic.\n\n4. **Client Preferences:** Many clients might hesitate to engage someone on a Tier 2 General visa due to concerns over legalities, visa compliance, and the long-term stability of hiring a contractor who may have to leave the client relationship if the visa situation changes.\n\n5. **Alternatives:** Some people in your situation look for roles within established companies willing to sponsor their visa, or they work through umbrella companies that can handle employment and payroll, although the latter option still requires direct employment rather than contracting.\n\n6. **Seek Guidance:** It might be helpful to consult with an immigration advisor or lawyer to explore your options further. They can provide specific advice related to your situation and ensure you're aware of any changes to visa policies.\n\n7. **Consider Permanent Roles:** If contracting opportunities are limited, you might consider seeking permanent roles, which are more likely to come with sponsorship for your visa type and can offer more stability.\n\nEnsure that any move you make complies with UK immigration laws and the terms of your visa to avoid jeopardizing your status.",
